        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>In this Problem, students encounter a variety of situations that require setting up proportions and solving for unknown values. Students should start to formalize the process of setting up equivalent ratios that make similar comparisons of quantities. In particular, scaling one ratio to find an unknown value in an equivalent ratio is highlighted as one strategy to help find unknown values.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {"content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>AoL: Analysis, Synthesis</p>", "<p>CCSSM: 7.RP.A.1, 7.RP. A.2, 7.RP. A.2.A, 7.RP. A.2.C, 7.RP.A.3</p>"]}},
      {
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Emerging Mathematical Ideas</strong></p>",
            "<p>Understand the need to compare ratios that relate the same two quantities in the same order: part-to-part, part-to-whole.</p>",
            "<p>Notice and use:</p>",
            "<ul><li>ratios with a focus on finding and using equivalent ratios to solve problems</li><li>begin to formalize the process of setting up proportions and solving for an unknow value</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {"display": "teacher", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>NWDYK</p>", "<p>How are proportions like other strategies that you have used to solve ratio problems?  How are they different?</p>"]}},
